=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dynamiteneon>DynamiteNeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Al's Underling</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/25/02 6:56:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4583.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.mangaden.com/pics/junk/b.jpg width=75 length=75></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How to get the cleanest scan from penciled artwork?</span><hr size=1> Well, the best way is to pencil cleanly and make sure your lines are wide and clear.  The wider the lines are, the easier it is to single them out.  <br>
<br>
Draw bigger, or if you can't do that, increase the size of the image in photoshop or whatever, play with the levels till it looks ok, then apply a bit of a gaussian blur to smooth things out before.  That seems to work ok for me.  Just do the blurring at the end though.<br>
<br>
if you have some particular drawings you're trying to clean, maybe you should post them so it's easier to spot your problems. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dynamiteneon>DynamiteNeon</A> at: 11/25/02 6:57:45 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=pigin>Pigin</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://pigin.freeyellow.com/SteinAvatar.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(11/27/02 8:35:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4583.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://mike.koolplace.com/Asuka_avatar.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How to get the cleanest scan from penciled artwork?</span><hr size=1> Hrmmm....I think I just need a new scanner<br>
